column14: FreeResponse
Both drugs are the same and patients can tolerate the side effects
Both drugs appear to be of equal cost and efficacy with minimal side effects, so it didn't matter which one he chose, both would be appropriate.
Because doctor had prescribed it.
I think that it is up to the doctor to prescribe whichever drug he thinks is fit. He went through the training and knows what to reccomend to people.
He would be familiar with Drug A from experience with his patients. Therefore, he feels drug A is a better choice for his patients.
The doctors should establish a standard in their clinic in order to avoid internal conflict and prescribing of unnecessary drugs.

There does not appear to be much difference between drug A and B, and both have been proven to be safe and effective.  It seems that whether a doctor prescribes drug A or B is just personal preference, so there was nothing wrong with Dr. Jones's decision.
Both drugs seem equal, so there's no reason as to not give them drug A.
It looks like drug A and B can do the job. I would just trust my doctor's decision. I am sure that he gets feedback from his patients that why he is making this decision.
Both medications are the same he choose the one that he preferred there shouldn't be any problem with that.
It seems both A and B are both appropriate. Nothing seems wrong.
because both medications are about the same
Both drugs are a viable option and have minimal side effects. Doesn't matter which drug he chooses.
There is no difference between both drugs.
There are drugs that can be used for multiple people, but different people might need different types of drugs. There should be options for each person.
Without knowing the side effects, I just think the doctor should be looking at those for each patient and then deciding which drug is right based on that.
I don't know enough about the situation to make a judgment.

From the information provided I feel that both medicines are effective. Dr. Jones wants to provide good treatment and feels that A is best in this case. I have to assume that he has good reasons for this.
Dr. Jones hasn't done anything wrong that I have read. It doesn't seem like he based his decision on any unethical premises.
Both drugs were extremely affordable. I did not see why it made a difference.

In this example, there was no significant difference given between drugs A and B. Both were deemed safe and effective. The doctor was motivated by the needs of his patients and in the interests of maintaining their health. In that case, his judgement to prescribe drug B should be respected.
Considering the information available to me, I don't see why prescribing drug A would be an issue.
because doctors at the clinic tend to choose either drug a or b. Given the information the drugs are mostly the same.

I don't see the particular difference between the two medications. There's a reason a qualified doctor would prescribe one medication over another. They're both the same price and are prescribed for the same reason, so it seems like he chose medication A for a reason.
It was based on my feelings about the situation.The facts also were important.

The intention behind the prescription is somewhat clearly mentioned. Drugs A and B seem to have similar properties and are tolerated well, so the question is not of being able to tailor a drug to a person but more about a preference on the doctor's part. This preference now is a bit of a gray area because I would like to know other factors that differentiate the two drugs, such as their price, insurance coverage or other ways in which there could be a conflict of interest on the part of the prescribing authority.
As both drugs seem to work well (and are affordable), it isn't morally wrong to begin with drug A to see how it effects the patient--as it can be changed later on if necessary.

I assume Dr. Jones is competent since he is practicing medicine and he is not alone in prescribing drug A.  If drug A side effects can be tolerated and is affordable then my assumption is that it's appropriate.  I would prefer to also know information about the drug's effectiveness.
It sounds like the effects and results gained from either type of medication is fine.  The choice does not seem relevant if the results are nearly identical.
is the personal opinion of the doctor, but both drugs are viable.
That is that doctors best recommendation and makes it fair that all patients are receiving the same treatment.

There's no basis to judge, because both drugs are good and other doctors prescribe both of them. I think it is reasonable to choose A, although I would have said "very appropriate" if there were more certainty that A was a better choice rather than just a fine choice.

Logically speaking, just because Dr. Jones wants to supply his patients with good treatment doesn't mean his decision is appropriate or a good one. He should choose medicine that is shown to cure the issue of high blood pressure as well as the medicine that has the least side effects.
Both medicines are effective and tolerable.
If both drugs are both effective then he was right in his decision to choose one of those drugs.
The doctor can choose to do what he feels is best. It is up to the patient to agree or disagree.
because he wants the best choice for the patient

Dr. Jones is treating the patients with Drug A which is almost exactly the same as B. I think considering the circumstances of the comparison its a smart move for the Dr to only prescribe drug A because it makes it easier to keep up with what his patients are on and what to expect. If drug B was "better" i would expect him to prescribe that, but based on the information provided i see no reason why its not appropriate for him to choose Drug A

Drug A has presumably been approved by the FDA, is affordable and has tolerable side effects. One drug is just as acceptable as the other in this case, so I have no reason to believe that the selection of Drug A is anything less than very appropriate.

As the professional, Dr. Jones has the responsibility to prescribe whichever medication he sees best fits his patient's needs. Therefore, his decision is highly appropriate since he ultimately gets to make the most appropriate medical decisions.
As a doctor he should be providing his patients with the most effective medication. If he feels that it is prescription A then he should be prescribing that.

According to the information given, both drugs are affordable and patients can tolerate the side effects, so regardless of which drug the Doctor prescribes the result will be the same, thus his decision is appropriate.
if both provide the same benefit and cost, with no problems ---  no reason not to prescribe the medication
I chose that it was very appropriate because both drugs were affordable and their patients were able to tolerate there side effects.
Just because an establishment prescribes only those 2 drugs, that doesn't mean there's not something else out there better that he should look into.
There is no comparison if A is better than B.
I choose it because its the best option for his patient with high blood pressure. And as a doctor working in the clinic, he probably know the best drug to prescribe.
Assuming the efficacy of the drugs is similar, the burdens to the patients in terms of cost are equal.
It sounds like the Doctor is doing the right thing because either medicine is suppose to work without side effects so whatever one he chooses is OK.
He chose drug A because it treats high blood pressure and there is no description of what drub B does.

You have indicated they are both affordable, effective, with tolerable side effects.  Without more detail, I could not think of anything that would sway me one way or the other as to judge his choice.  I do think 'affordable' and 'tolerable' are pretty subjective terms to apply to all patient sets, so I would want to know more about the difference in costs and side effects before I decided if it was appropriate for the doctor to have chosen drug 'B'.

Both drug A and drug B are good, appropriate choices. They both treat high blood pressure, have tolerable side effects and other doctors prescribe drug A like Dr. Jones. I chose "Somewhat Appropriate" because it isn't explicitly stated if Dr. Jones would allow a patient to switch to Drug B if the patient wanted to. I know the side effects are tolerable, but I think there should be a bit of leeway for patients in that regard to be able to see which one suits them best.
His objective is to help people control their blood pressure.  There are many options and ways to do that.
Given the information provided, I don't know any difference between drug A and B.  So seems appropriate to pick one of them

If there are 2 drugs that have both been approved by FDA, they both are affordable,side effects are tolerable and they appear to work, then it would be appropriate to prescribe either of the drugs. Usually it is whichever drug the individual Dr has had the most success with.
It doesn't necessarily say any difference between the two drugs so it does not warrant any positive or negative comparisons between them.

It is an appropriate medication, but it would've more appropriate to let patients know there are two medications that are available and give his recommendation based on his experience, but let the patient decide. This would likely encourage patients to speak up about minor side effects or concerns since they know there is an alternative.
you said he wants to provide good care, so he obviously has some reason to think that this drug is better for his patients than the other option.
Both drugs seem like they would be acceptable choices as the side effects of each can be tolerated by the patients. Additionally, both can treat the condition so either choice would be appropriate.
Both drugs are safe for the client and don't result in any real benefit to the doctor. There is reallreason why the doctors decision should be thought of as unreasonable.
Either drug is appropriate to treat the illness.
I chose option A because Dr. Jones behaved like a doctor should. Both medicines were about the same in terms of affordability and side effects, so it's appropriate to prescribe drug A.
It could be appropriate based on price and side effects.  I suppose the drugs effectiveness needs to be considered as well.  But there is no mention of it in the passage.
Both drugs provide the same benefit with the same costs. Doctor Jones choosing drug A has no appropriateness based on the provided information.

He doesn't have any evidence that this is not the best drug for the patients he sees. He is going with what he knows and all side effects are similar. There is no reason he shouldn't prescribe patients this drug, although he didn't do much of his own research.

I guess the doctor is choosing the drug he thinks is best for his patients. That being said, I think he should focus on teaching his patients to make lifestyle and diet changes instead to deal with their high blood pressure, but I guess this isn't an attractive option since it wouldn't make him any money.

The reason I chose this option is because both drugs A and B are used to treat high blood pressure. So, in this regard Doctor Jones's decision in prescribing drug A to his patients is very appropriate as the others doctors in this walk-in clinic either prescribe drug A or prescribe drug B to treat high blood pressure.
While both drugs are probably comparable with few differences I presume the doctor has researched both and decided A was the better alternative assuming he is not compensated.

It seems reasonable that doctor Jones just wants to make sure that his patients get the best possible treatment for their high blood pressure. in his opinion, that option is Drug A, so it makes sense that he chooses to prescribe that.
Both drugs seemed to be effective with equal side effects so either should be appropriate.
Both options are affordable and have manageable side affects.  Both options have similar risk vs rewards, so the doctor is not doing anything beneficial or negative.
He is giving medicine that will help patients with high blood pressure. They are affordable.
Drug A is known to treat high blood pressure. It makes sense to prescribe that drug.
His choice of drug to prescribe is his to decide based on professional opinion.
Since both drugs are affordable and patients can tolerate their side effects, I do not see what difference it makes which one he uses
Both drug A and drug B are affordable with tolerable side effects. So either option would be reasonable and okay for Doctor Jones to supply.

I don't  see what is wrong with his decision, since both drugs are about the same. I do not trust doctors, however, and the way they push drugs is criminal. The most moral decision in my opinion is to not prescribe anything.

It seems that Drug A and Drug B are similar enough that either drug can be used to treat high blood pressure. Because of such similarities, his decision to arbitrarily decide prescribing Drug A was somewhat appropriate. It is not very appropriate because he should do some more research to see if Drug A is indeed the superior drug.
Thre's no difference between the 2 drugs, so if Dr.Jones wants to use drug A on his patients, I can't see , why that should be inappropriate.
He chose the option that would help with the patient's condition.
I would guess that he has picked the drug that his patients have had a lot of success with. I have no problem if he prefers one drug over another if he gets good results.
I chose Drug A because Dr. Jones prescribes it to his patients. It must be the better choice then.
because as a doc, you should want to prescribe the best care possible to your patients. So therefore, if both are affordable but one is better than the other why not chose the best.
Both medications provide the same benefits and side effects. Therefore his decision is appropriate.
The ethical, clinical, and personal cost is equal for A and B.
It was just dependant on which  drug he wanted to give. There wasn't much other information to go off of.
If both medications are equally affordable and safe. Then it wouldn't make any difference which one the doctor prescribed.
Both the medications are affordable and viable.

I think it's appropriate for Dr. Jones to give his patient prescription A because he wants to provide good treatment to his patients and obviously Dr. Jones believes that prescription is the best option.
Drug A seems to be a safe and effective treatment for high blood pressure. If patients are being successfully treated with Drug A, then the decision is appropriate.
It mentions FDA approval but not weather the blood pressure pill A or B is approved. I would need more information to really say if A is a better choice than B
Doctor Jones chose an appropriate drug for his patients. There is no evidence that drug B is significantly better, so there is nothing wrong with choosing drug A.
It seems like either medicine is appropriate, so I think the doctor is using his background knowledge to make the best choice.

The information provided tells us that both choices for treatment of high blood pressure work well and are affordable. It is therefore appropriate for him to use his best judgment  to choose one drug over the other.
He did what was appropriate. It fit the situation since what he prescribed is specifically for what he was treating. He wants to give good treatment to all his patients, and follows through with it.

If they're both affordable and similar in side effects and results I don't see the problem. The only problem I could see is if A is his go to medicine and he would prescribe it over a patient's will or other needs.
I feel like generally speaking a drug known to be reliable and safe at a good price point is a wise choice. I don't feel like I know enough in this scenario to be positive it's the right choice.
Some patients responf better to certain drugs, all pateints shouldnt automaticlly be perscribed the sdame thing.
Either drug is fine and it doesn't seem like there's any difference between choosing either.

Both options have been approved by the fda, but there must still be subtle differences between the two that could inpact the use in different patients. I feel that it is never safe to assume the same drug will work the same on everyone.

If both drugs are affordable and patients can tolerate their side effects then it doesn't really mater which one is prescribed. Once the patient starts taking he medication then the doctor will know more about if that particular drug will work for his patient.
Maybe drug A is better for the patients and maybe Dr. Jones knows something that the other Doctors are not aware of.

I would feel slightly uncomfortable with this format. I feel there should be more consistency with the medications prescribed if patients are seeing whichever doctor is available within the same clinic.

Not every humans body works the same. A drug that may work for one individual may not work the same for another. Prescribing drugs is an educated guess and only with feedback from the patient can the doctor narrow down what works and doesn't work for certain patients. Therefore, I think that neither drug A or B is a better choice.
Medications are different for every different person, by just choosing a medication without knowing the specifics of each patient he is running risk of adverse side effects.
I AM REALLY NOT SURE ON THIS ONE, ITS MAY CROSS THE LINE ON MEDICAL ETHICS.
I chose somewhat appropriate because it is smart to use the drug that has the best results in treating high blood pressure.
Given the conditions of the program, the patients aren't being adversely affected.
I see no problwm with seeing which drug works better. Alternating the two drugs seems smart thing to do. Trial runs have usually proved to be productive.

It seems by engaging in this novel way t o determine which medication is best, the doctor is working for the benefit of his patients.  As long as the sample size is big enough, this seems like a reasonable thing to do.
It makes sense that a Doctor would want to use the drug that worked the best for high blood pressure The patients were gonna be on Drug A or Drug B either way.
I feel like it would be appropriate if the patients agree to join a trial and the random drug they are giving doesn't affect their health.
I think that if there are no large risks in either medication, it is very appropriate for the doctor to do this to make sure he picks the most effective medication.

He is ultimately seeking to improve care through more effective drugs. Because the drugs dont seem to have negative effects, it seems relatively ethical. However, I would be slightly concerned because he is being deceptive by not informing his patients.
I think that this is a great way to find out what medication works .  The doctor wants the best for his patients and what to figure out which medication is better.

Since both drugs are reasonably affordable and safe, i think it's appropriate to assign either drug to patients on a random basis. Doctor Jones' research will also have a positive effect later, when the more effective drug is the preferred one.
Because these are already being prescribed. So he's not giving unknown drugs to people. There is not risk
I feel like it's nice.

I would think it would produce the best overall results for the patients.  If certain patients then don't respond well to the best performing drug they could be switched to the lessor performing one and be monitored.
Approved products, the doctor is only trying to determine which is best. At least he's not on the payroll of drug company A or B

I think it's a good way to find out which drug is better however I'm not sure how moral or ethical it is. Each patient should be treated individually and prescribed whatever drug works best but if Dr. Jones does not know which drug works best I think this "experiment" is appropriate.

While the basis of his decision appears sound, ie both drugs are affordable, there is an even split between the doctors in his office that prescribe them, it still seems as if there should be some choice in prescribing them based on an individual patients response to the drug.  It would be to say, well pain relievers still do pretty much the same thing so take whatever you want, and that is not the case.

Considering both drugs are safe, effective, affordable and side affects are tolerable, I think what Dr. Jones is doing is commendable.  I would have a different view if we didn't know the effects of the drugs.
He choose the best thing for the patient. He is not truing to make money from them and put their life in danger.
He is trying to determine the better drug out of the two
He doesn't know which one is better so instead of giving drugs to patients arbitrarily, he's obtainining new information with his method.
seems like the best way to figure out which drug really is the better one.

Doctor Jones is trying to find which drug is the best one for his patients. Either drug is affordable and the side effects are tolerable, but no one knows whether Drug A or B is better. Finding which one is best seems like a no brainer.
I think he's making the right move for the most part. But sometime what works for someone may not work for the other.
Both drugs are approved by the FDA. The patients are not being given placebo. We don't know which drug will work best for all of the patients.
The patients should be aware of the study if they are part of it.  If he explains what he is doing and the potential differences between the two options then it might be okay.
I believe the doctor is trying to get the best results for his patients.
fairness
He honestly wants the best for his patients and since the drugs are apparently similar and he's unsure about which is better, he decides to test it
Thats how he can decide which is better.
I choose my answer because for him to be consistent and know which drugs works best, he must have to experiment on them

Trail and error is the only way in this case to determine what is the best drug to use for these patients. Being able to figure out what medication works best with less effects I think would be the goal for anyone.

I think Doctor Jones's decision is somewhat appropriate for the current medical industry because this is similar to what many doctors actually do. All patients should be aware that when they enter the doctors office they may be subject to guinea-pig-like testing.

It seems like he has no great preference at the moment. Other doctors could give him equally valid arguments for A or B, so he is being open minded. In the end he will make a better and more educated decision.

As long as both drugs are effective, safe, and affordable to the patients this does not seem inappropriate. He should consider telling the patients but it isn't a necessity. Telling them what he is doing and more importantly why he is doing it will build a relationship of trust between doctor and patient.
He looks at the patient and sees what is best for him.  He takes things on a case by case basis.

Because if both drugs are just as affordable with equivalent side affects, I think it is reasonable for the doctor to manage his patients with both medications so that he can determine for himself which medication he prefers to prescribe. I think that it is better than only going based on the opinions with other doctors. I do think that he still needs to keep an open conversation with his patients and inform them that there are options other than the one medication that they are given.
Although this is logical methodology, the literature and Peer review available for the drugs should be highly considered as well.
Medications are trial and error.

i think that is appropriate the doctors  Jone decision. he is just looking for the drugs that have the best result over all the patients. he is looking for the best probability over a series of trials.
Just seems reasonable. Of course I am assuming there are no other factors influencing his choices.

I believe it is appropriate if the patients have no preference.  Both drugs are approved and patients are typically able to handle the side effects of each.  It is a good way to see which one is actually most effective without added risk to patients.
Since both drugs are appropriate he wants to go a step further and learn which is better with his group of patients rather than choosing randomly.

If the drugs treat the same problem, are both affordable, both have limited side affects, and the doctor receives no kick-backs from either drug company, the frequency or randomness of the prescription doesn't matter, in my opinion.

If there are no known differences prior to the experiment, then it seems like it would be reasonable to take advantage of the fact that the patients would have already been assigned one of those drugs. However, it would be appropriate if Doctor Jones let his patients be aware of the experiment that he is conducting.

It's a reasonable way to determine how effective the seperate drugs are. The only issue is that it's not a proper scientific test. There's no control group, the patients haven't given permission, its not being done under close observation, and everyone's different so the data won't be completely accurate as the drugs may react differently depending on the person. All that being said, if the choice is drug A or drug B and he has no way of knowing which is better, and there is no danger to the patients, if he notices one is more effective than the other this would be a sort of alright way to go about testing it.
Both are safe and can be effective.  Dr jones is using sound methods to determine which is better.
I think it is okay as long as he does all the research and talks to the other doctors to find out why they choose drug a or drug B.
He is trying to prescribe the best drugs to his patients n

I believe it is appropriate because it is one of the only ways we can learn what works.  We need to test  on people to understand the outcomes, and in the long run the ones who had the worse treatment can switch.
Dr. Jones probably shouldn't be running an experiment an unknowing participants, but he's doing it for good reason and may result in positive benefits.
Although the experiment didn't seem 100 percent scientific, it may provide some insight into how effective each medication is.

It is somewhat appropriate to attempt to see if one is really working better than the other.  It could help in his choice to provide the better one.  I year is enough time to see if there is actually any result that could benefit his patients.
I choose my answer because a control group was used which is the way I understand studies should go when you are trying to find out the side effects of something.
he is doing his own study to see which drug works the best on patients around his area.
If both medications are effective and safe, it is fine for him to use the "random" method with prescriptions until he sees which one actually is most effective.
Because he will  then know for sure the affects of the drug

Neither medication has been proven to be harmful.  Doctor Jones wants to see which of the two medications has better results for his future patients which will include the ones in his current experiment.
Doctor Jones in not endangering his patients or preventing them from receiving treatment so his actions are approrpriate
The experiment will show which drug is most effective, so they can stop prescribing the less effective drugs.

He's using the drugs as they are intended and treating the condition. It is not harming anyone. I said somewhat instead of Very appropriate because some might say he's making people apart of a study without consent, but I'm not sure that's the case,
If both drugs are about the relatively same price and have similar side effects it doesn't do any harm to split the prescriptions. It is a good way to determine what works best.

The patients are already randomly receiving drug A or B with no control over the decision. Also, both drugs are approved for treating high blood pressure. Dr. Jones's decision is not changing the status quo in how patients are treated and does not represent any additional danger to them.

Because he is using 2 approved drugs and attempting to determine the best solution for his patients, he is doing something appropriate.  The only problem I have is that the narrative above did not describe if he was informing his patients about his test...
it is a common procdure to try different mediations to see what works best,

The drug should already have been studied on various groups. Each drug should have its own benefits and drawbacks so this should already be known. The doctor needs to give the drugs to best meet the patients needs based on research already done.
Because patients shouldnt be treated as human guinea pigs. The doctor should find another way to do his research.
He should not be running experiments on his own without the consent of his patients, even if the two drugs are approved by the FDA.

He is making a decision based on a very small study group and then is going to basically ignore one of the drugs.  Different people respond differently to drugs - you want to prescribe the one that works best for them as individuals.

It seems to me that the doctor is running experiments off the top of his head, without any controls. The other issue I have is that what if one drug is totally ineffective or has really bad side-effects. Does this mean at the end he will prescribe the other drug only - going forward. Some how I feel that he has used people as guinea pigs.
I think medicine is primarily done on these types of experiments to get the best results.  I don't think he is doing anything wrong by trying them for a year and seeing what the best outcome is.
It's more appropriate from him to make an informed decision as a doctor about each drug and prescribe them to his patients based on individual needs
The doctor wants to do a good job for his patients but drug studies need more control of variables before drawing such conclusions.

Why would a doctor be able to randomly assign medication to his patients without their consent? Unless they were part of a research study where they were aware they may not be told the specific medication they are taking, this seems inappropriate.
I think the year is a good length of time to conduct a study. It sounds like he has the right idea.
It is not his place to experiment the drugs on patients. They have trials for doing such things in a safe environment and should be done before the drug is on the market.
He is not in the business of don't clinical research. He should prescribe what he thinks is best.
he should which drug is appropiate for each patient-- not a year long experiment.

I think Doctor Jonesâ€™ decision is somewhat inappropriate because the patients are not being informed about his experiment. When patients are being given mediciation, I strongly believe they should be informed about what they are being given so they can decide if the they want to take the medicine.
Using patience as guinea pigs is a bad idea. Patients are not lab rats, and should be given the drug that best suits them based on their own medical history.

If I were a patient, I would like to know if I am involved in an experiment.  You never know how a drug will affect someone because we are all different.  I think the Doctor would need to let his patients know up front and ask for their permission to participate and then assign which drug he would like to give them and proceed with the study/experiment from there.
Such an experiment is only appropriate if the patients consent to it. In the example, it does not sound as though the patients have consented to this approach.
This kind of experimenting should be done before the drug hits the market and there is probably research on this, so he need not spend time experimenting on his own patients
Patients did not consent to the experiement. There is an appropriate way to administer this and using paying patients is not the way- this is better suited for a research trial.
He will not tell his patients that they are participating in this study.  That is wrong.

It is inappropriate to subject people to a test without informing them and obtaining their consent. I do not find it as wholly inappropriate because he seems to be doing it for altruistic reasons and the fact that both drugs seem to be viable drugs for the problem.
I dunno. Only limiting patients to one drug will limit potential for variability and improvement.

He cannot just give only one drug at the end because some patients may not be able to take that drug, and in that case will need the other one. It also depends on various complications of the drugs and how they interact with each person on an individual level.
because he is running experiments on victims

With the information available, it sounds like this "research" is unlikely to harm the patients or reduce the efficacy of their treatment.  However, as I understand it, it does not meet the standards of clinical research because it lacks a control group and the patients do not give informed consent.
One should not experiment outcome of a drug on real patients. It should be done in a lab. I don't think it is a good practice to test it out on real patients.
It seems as though the doctor is performing his own clinical trial on patients without their consent. At the same time, the patients are receiving these drugs regardless of his test.
Patients should never be an "experiment".  The doctor should prescribe whatever drug that has the least amount of complication given if both drugs have the same overall success.

The doctor should do what he thinks is best for each individual patient based on their situation instead of doing his own "experiment". I think he should look at research already done and make his decisions based on that instead of within his own clinic. His information may not be consistent if people who come to the walk-in clinic see a different physician each time.
all patients should be allowed the same health care and should not be subject to an experiment without consent.

There's not enough information to decide which of A or B are the better drug objectively. But for efficiency's sake, it does make sense for Doctor Jones to choose one drug for his patients and go with that.
There doesn't seem to be any negative information on either drug so his choice was appropriate.

Since there seems to be not much difference in the medication I could see no reason to why not to prescribe drug b. I think it depends on it the patient responds to the treatment to the course that should be used.
It looks like both drugs are acceptable based off the limited info on drug.

It may be that A is better for some patients and B is better for others, but the question doesn't give us enough information to know, so I went with "somewhat appropriate" rather than "very appropriate."

Since the doctors in the clinic where Doctor Jones works have prescribed both A & B and both are affordable with tolerable side effects, either drug chosen by Doctor Jones would have been an appropriate choice.

I feel this is an appropriate choice because both are affordable and effective. The doctor's experience causes him to prefer Drug B over Drug A so it's acceptable and predictable that he will choose that where appropriate for his patients.
Both Drug A and Drug B will treat High Blood Pressure with acceptable risks.
He is a doctor so if both drugs do relatively the same thing than he can prescribe either.
he is tyrying to overall help his patients. In the long run he is helping them.
Both of the drugs appear to be the same. Either one would be a good choice for the patient.
Both drugs seem to be equally good options, so it's reasonable to pick B.
If they're both of equal price, and effectiveness, there is no reason why medication B would be an issue.

It sounds as if both medications are appropriate for the diagnosis the doctor came up with. Since there doesn't seem to be a difference between the two him prescribing one over the other doesn't matter.
He is prescribing a drug that is effective and tolerated.
Because either medication would address the patients needs and be affordable for them as well.

Several drugs are available and approved by the FDA to treat high blood pressure. Both are affordable and have tolerable side effects. As long as there is no noticeable difference between the two drugs, the decision was very appropriate on the doctor's behalf.
Doctor Jones is entitled to prescribe the drug he believes works best for his patients.
Lacking any further information I'm unable to see any negative effects of the doctor's decision.

Without any other extenuating circumstances like being paid by one drug company or the other, Dr. Jones seems to think the patient would be best served with B. This in my mind would be based on his training and experience.
He may of done research on the two medications and noticed B was more effective or that more patients liked that medicine or had better outcomes.
Both drugs are acceptable medications to give to the patient.
Doctor Jones's choice of providing his patients with drug B "to provide good treatment to his patients" suggests that he has less confidence in the effectiveness of drug A.

Both drugs are described as being affordable, and, having no distinct differences with regards to side effects. However, there may be personal preference, so, it may be advisable that Dr Jones discusses both options with the patients, rather than deciding on only a single option. Additionally, the Dr may want to consider other factors that may drive decision outcome.
